**When migrating routes, be careful to plan and follow existing rules.**

Use these guidelines when you are migrating code from the legacy tRPC-based implementation at `apps/server/`, into the new Hono, openapi-based implementation at `apps/api/`.

The legacy tRPC routes are located in `apps/server/src/trpc/routes/`.

The new OpenAPI routes are located in `apps/api/src/routes/`.

- ALWAYS follow the rules defined in [hono-openapi-route.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/hono-openapi-route.mdc) extremely carefully.
- Each route should be cleanly mapped to the new `apps/api/src/routes/` format, keeping the directory flat.
- Migrate both the route and tests. Always ensure that the route is registered when you are finished.
- Update the route name to follow the guidelines of OpenAPI. (e.g. `bottleById` would become `bottleDetails`).
- If a route exists for multiple inputs (e.g. `countryById` and `countryBySlug`), it should be migrated to a single union-type parameter on the OpenAPI endpoint.
- If you're using code from `@peated/server` in the migration, ensure the code is ported over to the new `@peated/api` codebase. That is, duplicate the code if its not already present.
- NEVER make changes to the `tsconfig` files or any build system configuration.

## Tests

- ALWAYS look at existing tests for the route, and ensure every single test still exists.
- Look for opportunities to improve test coverage if there are obvious concerns missing.
- The existing tests will always be in the same directory as the route definition, using the `.test.ts` extension (vs just `.ts`).
- ALWAYS run tests after you migrate a route to ensure its still correct. Use the following from the workspace root:

```shell
pnpm --filter ./apps/api test --run [newRouteName]
```
